        <!-- Abstract Section -->
        <section id="abstract" class="mb-20 max-w-4xl mx-auto">
            <h2 class="section-title">Abstract</h2>
            <div class="bg-gray-800 p-8 rounded-lg shadow-lg text-gray-300 text-lg leading-relaxed text-justify">
                <p>The remote locations ideal for astronomical observatories—both on Earth and in space—create significant data transmission bottlenecks. With modern observatories being incredibly expensive, any improvement in lossless data compression can translate to billions of dollars worth of additional science. While traditional compression methods are manually designed, neural data compression offers the potential to learn highly efficient algorithms directly from data. By capturing the unique spatial, temporal, and wavelength structures in astronomical images, these learned methods can outperform classical techniques. This paper introduces <strong>AstroCompress</strong>, a neural compression challenge for astrophysics data. It features four new datasets and one legacy dataset, all containing 16-bit unsigned integer imaging data across various modes: space-based, ground-based, multi-wavelength, and time-series.</p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- The Problem Section -->
        <section id="problem" class="mb-20 max-w-4xl mx-auto">
            <h2 class="section-title">The Challenge: An Explosion of Astronomical Data</h2>
            <div class="bg-gray-800 p-8 rounded-lg shadow-lg text-gray-300 text-lg leading-relaxed text-justify">
                <p>Astronomy data volumes are growing at a superexponential rate, increasing by a factor of nearly 1000x every 10 years. This rapid growth places an immense burden on our ability to transmit and store data, threatening to stall scientific progress. The development of exascale supercomputers is a direct response to this data deluge. Advanced compression is not just a convenience—it's a critical necessity to ensure we can continue to collect and analyze the vast amounts of data from radio astronomy, satellite imagery, and other large-scale scientific endeavors. While lossless methods are safe, carefully designed lossy compression may unlock orders-of-magnitude improvements in data handling pipelines.</p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Dataset Section -->
        <section id="dataset" class="mb-20">
            <h2 class="section-title">The AstroCompress Benchmark</h2>
            <p class="text-center text-lg text-gray-400 max-w-3xl mx-auto mb-12">
                AstroCompress provides a diverse suite of datasets to spur the development of novel compression techniques tailored for the unique challenges of astronomical data.
            </p>
            <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
                <!-- Card 1 -->
                <div class="card">
                    <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1614726365953-53131ada43a4?q=80&w=2070&auto=format&fit=crop" alt="Pillars of Creation" class="rounded-md mb-4 w-full h-48 object-cover" onerror="this.onerror=null;this.src='https://placehold.co/600x400/1E293B/94A3B8?text=Image+Error';">
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-2">Space-Based Imagery</h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-400">High-resolution images captured from orbital telescopes, characterized by low noise and high dynamic range.</p>
                </div>
                <!-- Card 2 -->
                <div class="card">
                    <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1534533983685-c7b0e245df9a?q=80&w=2070&auto=format&fit=crop" alt="Very Large Array in New Mexico" class="rounded-md mb-4 w-full h-48 object-cover" onerror="this.onerror=null;this.src='https://placehold.co/600x400/1E293B/94A3B8?text=Image+Error';">
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-2">Ground-Based Imagery</h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-400">Data from terrestrial observatories, which may include atmospheric noise and other artifacts.</p>
                </div>
                <!-- Card 3 -->
                <div class="card">
                    <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1634411312134-5178e5a74695?q=80&w=1932&auto=format&fit=crop" alt="Multi-wavelength view of a galaxy" class="rounded-md mb-4 w-full h-48 object-cover" onerror="this.onerror=null;this.src='https://placehold.co/600x400/1E293B/94A3B8?text=Image+Error';">
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-2">Multi-Wavelength Data</h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-400">Images captured across different spectral bands, presenting opportunities for cross-channel compression.</p>
                </div>
                 <!-- Card 4 -->
                <div class="card">
                    <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1506703119495-ac221a6c1269?q=80&w=2070&auto=format&fit=crop" alt="Long exposure of star trails" class="rounded-md mb-4 w-full h-48 object-cover" onerror="this.onerror=null;this.src='https://placehold.co/600x400/1E293B/94A3B8?text=Image+Error';">
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-2">Time-Series Data</h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-400">Sequences of images observing the same celestial object over time, ideal for temporal compression models.</p>
                </div>
                 <!-- Card 5 -->
                <div class="card">
                    <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1599391102517-133d2c139c89?q=80&w=1974&auto=format&fit=crop" alt="Archival photographic plate of the sky" class="rounded-md mb-4 w-full h-48 object-cover" onerror="this.onerror=null;this.src='https://placehold.co/600x400/1E293B/94A3B8?text=Image+Error';">
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-2">Legacy Astronomical Data</h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-400">A well-established dataset included for benchmarking against existing and future methods.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

